{"id":"1901.10428","submitter":"Giacomo Guarnieri PhD","authors":"Giacomo Guarnieri, Gabriel T. Landi, Stephen R. Clark, John Goold","title":"Thermodynamics of precision in quantum non equilibrium steady states","comments":"6 pages of main text + 7 pages of Appendices","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 1, 033021 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.1.033021","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Autonomous engines operating at the nano-scale can be prone to deleterious\nfluctuations in the heat and particle currents which increase, for fixed power\noutput, the more reversible the operation regime is. This fundamental trade-off\nbetween current fluctuations and entropy production forms the basis of the\nrecently formulated thermodynamic uncertainty relations (TURs). However, these\nrelations have so far only been derived for classical Markovian systems and can\nbe violated in the quantum regime. In this paper we show that the geometry of\nquantum non-equilibrium steady-states alone, already directly implies the\nexistence of a TUR, but with a looser bound. The geometrical nature of this\nresult makes it extremely general, establishing a fundamental limit for the\nthermodynamics of precision. Our proof is based on the McLennan-Zubarev\nensemble, which provides an exact description of non-equilibrium steady-states.\nWe first prove that the entropy production of this ensemble can be expressed as\na quantum relative entropy. The TURs are then shown to be a direct consequence\nof the quantum Cramer-Rao bound, a fundamental result from parameter estimation\ntheory. By combining techniques from many-body physics and information\nsciences, our approach also helps to shed light on the delicate relationship\nbetween quantum effects and current fluctuations in autonomous machines.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 29 Jan 2019 17:58:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","create