{"id":"1901.10797","submitter":"Maurizio Fagotti","authors":"Maurizio Fagotti","title":"On the size of the space spanned by a nonequilibrium state in a quantum\n  spin lattice system","comments":"25 pages, 7 figures; new appendix with a proof that the energy\n  cumulants are extensive whenever the Hamiltonian is quasilocal and the state\n  has finite correlation lengths","journal-ref":"SciPost Phys. 6, 059 (2019)","doi":"10.21468/SciPostPhys.6.5.059","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech math-ph math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the time evolution of a state in an isolated quantum spin lattice\nsystem with energy cumulants proportional to the number of the sites $L^d$. We\ncompute the distribution of the eigenvalues of the time averaged state over a\ntime window $[t_0,t_0+t]$ in the limit of large $L$. This allows us to infer\nthe size of a subspace that captures time evolution in $[t_0,t_0+t]$ with an\naccuracy $1-\\epsilon$. We estimate the size to be $\n\\frac{\\sqrt{2\\mathfrak{e}_2}}{\\pi}\\mathrm{erf}^{-1}(1-\\epsilon)\nL^{\\frac{d}{2}}t$, where $\\mathfrak{e}_2$ is the energy variance per site, and\n$\\mathrm{erf}^{-1}$ is the inverse error function.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Jan 2019 13:01:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 4 Feb 2019 17:55:55 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 11 Mar 2019 10:32:54 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 29 Apr 2019 13:02:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-15"}
